{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"504"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/504"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.19,0.37,0.37,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"439"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents with a 24 hour history of increasing redness in his left eye. There is no associated pain. There is no history of eye trauma or insect bites. He does not have any changes to his vision. The photograph shows his eye (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dacryocystitis","Blepharitis","Hordeolum","Chalazion","Hypopyon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Echalazion\u003C/strong\u003E, with an obvious collection of meibomian gland oil at the back edge of the lid. These lesions present as a painless swelling on the inner surface of the eyelid. It is the most common inflammatory eyelid lesion and occurs secondary to blocked meibomian glands. In this instance the blocked pore may be secondary to blepharitis. The meibomian glands produce oil that lubricates the surface of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehordeolum\u003C/strong\u003E (stye) is a small, red, painful lump around an eyelash due to an acute folliculitis. This is an infectious obstruction. A hordeolum can also form on the inner eyelid and can easily be mistaken for a chalazion. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E will present with ocular irritation along with erythema, scales and crusting at the eyelid margin. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypopyon\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammatory cells in the anterior chamber - this is not seen in the image. \u003Cstrong\u003EDacrocystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of the lacrimal sac secondary to nasolacrimal duct obstruction and acutely presents with pain, erythema and oedema over the lacrimal sac which is above the medial canthus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A chalazion is a non-infectious obstruction of a meibomian gland."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"504"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17424"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17424"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b1e3fd3-aa75-4452